00:10:05.862 --> 00:10:13.552
Indeed, Edison was the first person to take the idea of being an inventor to a completely new level.

00:10:14.232 --> 00:10:22.662
He wanted to industrialise the process of invention, and in 1876 he set up an “invention

00:10:22.712 --> 00:10:29.802
factory” - his innovative research and development facility, called the Menlo Park Laboratory.

00:10:30.692 --> 00:10:37.932
There, Edison employed a large team of people who carried out research under his direction.

00:10:39.252 --> 00:10:44.902
The idea was to churn out, to produce, a constant supply of new

00:10:44.902 --> 00:10:50.582
inventions in all manner of fields, with Edison very much at the helm.

00:10:51.612 --> 00:10:56.412
Reportedly his vision was for the laboratory to make one minor

00:10:56.582 --> 00:11:01.062
breakthrough every 10 days and a major breakthrough once a month.

00:11:02.222 --> 00:11:07.122
Edison was legally credited with most of the lab’s inventions, it was

00:11:07.132 --> 00:11:12.152
his name on the patents, even though it was certainly a team effort, it

00:11:12.152 --> 00:11:17.062
was literally an invention factory, but only one man took the credit.

00:11:18.422 --> 00:11:23.002
This approach to invention was extremely novel for the era.

00:11:23.662 --> 00:11:29.762
If you compare Edison’s approach to that of solitary geniuses, such as Nikola

00:11:29.762 --> 00:11:35.282
Tesla, who mainly worked alone, you can see why Edison’s more business-like

00:11:35.282 --> 00:11:40.532
approach to invention was more productive and ultimately financially successful.

