After all, being successful is as much about how you

00:13:21.452 --> 00:13:24.372
deal with your setbacks as well as your achievements.

00:13:25.592 --> 00:13:32.492
Aside from improvement to the telegraph system, Edison made headway in improving the telephone, as

00:13:32.492 --> 00:13:39.072
well as inventing something called the phonograph - a type of early recording and playback device.

00:13:40.412 --> 00:13:45.192
Edison’s phonograph, which he released in 1877 when he was

00:13:45.212 --> 00:13:49.892
only 30 years old, made the young man a celebrity overnight.

00:13:50.812 --> 00:13:56.642
While the phonograph itself had limitations, the fact that Edison was able to record

00:13:56.882 --> 00:14:03.122
and playback his own voice with it was almost bordering on magic for most people.

00:14:04.172 --> 00:14:08.272
The phonograph earned Edison the nickname, “The Wizard of

00:14:08.272 --> 00:14:12.992
Menlo Park”, and the Washington Post labelled him a “genius”.

00:14:14.062 --> 00:14:17.402
But his most important invention was still to come.

00:14:18.132 --> 00:14:22.962
When you think of Thomas Edison, perhaps you think of the man who invented the light bulb.

00:14:23.632 --> 00:14:30.212
Now strictly speaking, he didn’t actually invent the light bulb, rather he improved upon

00:14:30.262 --> 00:14:36.902
previous versions to create a better model that was also commercially and economically viable.

00:14:38.624 --> 00:14:59.254
Unlike previous light bulbs, Edison's light bulb was the first one that

00:14:59.254 --> 00:15:02.111
was long-lasting enough to make it a practical choice for widespread use.

00:15:02.111 --> 00:15:02.555
But he wasn’t content with just inventing the light bulb.

00:15:02.555 --> 00:15:02.692
He wanted to create and control the electrical system that would power these lights.

00:15:02.692 --> 00:15:05.419
However, while Edison’s light bulb was a resounding success, his

00:15:05.719 --> 00:15:10.279
electrical distribution system came up against stiff competition.

00:15:11.369 --> 00:15:17.029
This battle to dominate the electricity distribution market would become known

00:15:17.239 --> 00:15:22.299
as the “War of the Currents”, a topic we’ll cover in detail in the next episode.

00:15:22.879 --> 00:15:29.769
This “war” pitted Edison, with his firm belief in something called DC supply,

00:15:29.999 --> 00:15:36.799
against George Westinghouse, amongst others, who advocated for the use of AC current.

00:15:37.709 --> 00:15:44.389
In short, Edison’s DC supply system had several disadvantages compared to AC.

00:15:45.159 --> 00:15:51.559
Mainly, AC could travel further, so it was more suitable for supplying the vast

00:15:51.559 --> 00:15:57.039
majority of customers and it didn’t require power plants on every street corner.

00:15:57.759 --> 00:16:04.709
Edison’s DC system was really only practical in very densely populated areas, and he

00:16:04.709 --> 00:16:11.299
eventually lost the battle for his DC system to be the standard electrical system in America.

00:16:12.149 --> 00:16:18.539
Now, as I said, we’ll cover this in great detail in the next episode, but this “War of

00:16:18.539 --> 00:16:24.424
the Currents” was a pivotal period where Edison’s true character really comes to light.

00:16:25.694 --> 00:16:34.439
He was a fierce competitor, not afraid to play dirty and smear his rivals, and this unwillingness

00:16:34.439 --> 00:16:40.779
to give in or admit defeat would eventually result in his losing control of his company.

00:16:41.729 --> 00:16:48.029
In other areas, when Edison got it wrong, he wasn’t afraid to make a quick U-turn.

00:16:49.019 --> 00:16:55.749
For example, his short-lived foray into the toy market, when he created talking dolls.

00:16:56.409 --> 00:17:02.399
Edison created smaller versions of his phonograph and placed them inside dolls.

00:17:03.199 --> 00:17:06.139
However, the end results didn’t go to plan.

00:17:06.819 --> 00:17:11.689
